@node "Installation" "Installation"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Dislaimer"


@{_Section "Installation"}

@{LIndent 2}
1) @{LIndent 5}With your Amiga turned off, plug the Palm cradle into an available serial port.  If your Amiga only has a 25-pin serial port then a 9-pin to 25-pin adapter will be required to plug the Palm's cradle into the Amiga's standard serial port.@{LIndent 2}


2) @{LIndent 5}Use the Installer to copy the Spitfireý files to your hard drive.  The installer uses the standard Amiga installer program and will install Spitfireý and its appropriate files onto your hard drive.@{LIndent 2}
@{Line}
@{Line}
When Spitfireý is executed for the fist time on a system, it will ask the user:@{par}

1) @{LIndent 5}To set up the preferences and serial port settings that the cradle is connected to.@{LIndent 2}


2) @{LIndent 5}To perform a HotSync of the Palm (therefore be sure to have your Palm ready and its cradle connected to your Amiga).@{LIndent 2}


This first time procedure will allow Spitfireý to establish the proper accounts on your Palm and Amiga.@{par}

If your Palm has already been HotSync with another computer, then Spitfireý will recognize this and create a new account on your Amiga.  It will not overwrite a user name established on a Palm unless specifically told to do so.

@endnode



@node "Usage" "Usage"
@next "TipsAndTricks"
@prev "Installation"


@{_Section "Usage"}

Spitfireý consists of two main applications:@{Line}

@{JLeft}@{LIndent 0}(1) Hotsync Manager (SpitfireHSM)@{LIndent 6}@{par}
This is the core of Spitfireý, and controls all the hotsync procedures.  Since HSM is an MUI application you can use the MUI prefs to set many of its features and look.  The HSM also gives access to customization of the serial port for hotsyncing, viewing of log files, and customizing of available conduits.
@{LIndent 2}@{Line}

@{JLeft}@{LIndent 0}(2) Desktop Application Manager (SpitfireDAM)@{LIndent 6}@{par}
This is a small program that allows easy access to the desktop applications.  It can be launced from the HSM or from the Workbench.

@{LIndent 0}


@{_Section "Conduits"}

A conduit determines how records are handled during a hotsync.  Each application has its own conduit, or uses the normal system conduit for hotsyncing.


Spitfireý defaults to synchronizing of all files between the handheld device and the Amiga.  Generally, you should leave the settings to synchronize all files.


In addition to the standard Address Book, Date Book, Memo Pad, and To Do List conduits, Spitfireý has a System and Install conduits.


The System conduit backs up the system information stroed in your handheld device.  The default setting for this conduit is Mirror backups, which will maintain mirror copies of system information on the handheld and the Amiga; in otherwords, files are synchronized.  Partial backup will only backup application which have a "backup" flag set for them by the application itself.  Complete backup will copy all files from the handheld to the Amiga.


The Install conduit is used to install PalmOS applications.


@{i}Refer to the Palm's User manual for help with terms and operation.@{ui}

@endnode



